    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.8.0-dev-985-gf9c183c0c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nNot relevant\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nNot relevant\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nNot relevant\n\n### Installation\n\nBuilt from source\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nWith `init.lua` being:\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, \"Foobar\", { fg = 'fg' })\r\n```\r\n\r\nDo:\r\n```\r\nnvim --clean -u init.lua\r\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAs stated in the documentation of `nvim_set_hl` the `\"fg\"` and `\"bg\"` values should be usable.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nThey are not.\r\n\r\n```\r\nError detected while processing .../init.lua:\r\nE5113: Error while calling lua chunk: .../init.lua:1: 'fg' is not a valid color\r\nstack traceback:\r\n        [C]: in function 'nvim_set_hl'\r\n        .../init.lua:1: in main chunk\r\n\r\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": ">    Note:\r\n>       The fg and bg keys also accept the string values `\"fg\"` or `\"bg\"`\r\n>       which act as aliases to the corresponding foreground and background\r\n>       values of the Normal group. **If the Normal group has not been defined,\r\n>       using these values results in an error.**\r\n\r\n...which I believe is not the case with `--clean`.\r\n\r\n\r\n(See also `highlight.c`, line 415ff.)",
